      "value": "Oceanside Unified is a large K-12 district on the North Coast of San Diego County. About 3,251 of its students have an IEP, and 693 of them \u2014 roughly 21% \u2014 have an autism (ASD) eligibility. Around 42% of those autistic students spend most of the school day in a general-education classroom."
    },
    "what_this_means_for_parents": {
      "ai_disclaimer": "This summary was written by an AI model from the data points in this profile. The underlying numbers come from public California government sources, but the narrative is AI-written and may contain inaccuracies. Verify specific claims directly with the school district before making decisions.",
      "ai_generated": true,
      "ai_generated_at": "2026-05-17T21:27:27Z",
      "ai_model": "claude-opus (via Claude Code session)",
      "based_on_sources": [
        "cde_spedps",
        "ca_dashboard"
      ],
      "value": "About 42% of autistic students in this district are in a general-education classroom for most of the day, with around 3% in a fully separate setting. Among all students with disabilities, a broader group than autism alone, 61% are in general-education classrooms most of the day. On 2024-25 state tests, students with disabilities scored about 106 points below standard in English and 133 below in math, while students overall were 25 and 56 points below. Students with disabilities were chronically absent at about 32% (compared with 23% for all students) and suspended at about 6% (compared with 3%)."
    }
  },
